ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Fig. 7
                        , the binding constant of G-CDs and Ag+ was determined as 9.25 × 103 M−1, which also indicated the binding strength between G-CDs and Ag+ was greatly strong. Since the G-CDs has a high binding affinity with Ag+ by the specific recognition group of guanine, the excited electrons transfer from the G-CDs to the unoccupied orbital of Ag+ through nonradioactive electron-transfer progress was much easily (Scheme 2
                        ). In order to further confirm the feasibility of the electron transfer from the G-CDs to Ag+, the energy levels of the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (ELUMO) and the highest occupied molecular orbital (EHOMO) of the G-CDs were calculated as −3.53 eV and −6.71 eV, respectively (Fig. S7), and the ELUMO of Ag+ was −5.20 eV according to the previous work [44]. Thus, the excited electron transfer from G-CDs to the orbitals of Ag+ was allowed with fitting energy. Moreover, the cyclic voltammetry measurements of G-CDs with different metal ions were shown in Fig. S8. It was obvious that the reduction potential change of G-CDs/Ag+ complex (from −1.18 V to −0.98 V) was higher than that of G-CDs/Fe3+, G-CDs/Cu2+, and G-CDs/Hg2+, which indicated that G-CDs/Ag+ complex was stronger than other G-CDs/metal complexes [45], subsequently result in the highly selective fluorescent response of G-CDs towards Ag+ against other typical metal quenchers. In addition, the FL lifetime was measured to be 7.50 ns (τ1 = 3.97 ns, τ2 = 10.27 ns) before introducing Ag+, but decreased to 5.44 ns (τ1 = 2.14 ns, τ2 = 7.86 ns) after the addition of 100 μM Ag+ (Fig. S6b), which suggested a dynamic quenching occurred [46,47].
